## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort to Cooperative Cancellation

### Pattern Classification

This is **timeout enforcement** — `Thread.Abort` kills a thread that exceeds a time limit. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Key APIs Being Removed

| .NET Framework API | Why it breaks | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `thread.Abort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `SYSLIB0006` / no-op | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if Task.Run's body doesn't check it.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ae.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and must respond to cancellation

The version above unblocks the *caller* at timeout, but the delegate keeps running in the background. To make the work actually stop, pass the token through:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(token), token)
                   .WaitAsync(token)
                   .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example — work cooperates by checking the token:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | Guidance |
|---|---|
| **Work keeps running after timeout** | `Thread.Abort` forcibly killed the thread; cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work` never checks the token, it runs to completion in the background. Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints. |
| **Blocking calls ignore the token** | `Thread.Sleep`, raw socket reads, etc. don't check tokens. Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. Use async I/O overloads that accept `CancellationToken`. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the top-level orchestration point (here, to convert to `TimeoutException`). Let it propagate everywhere else. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If you can't modify the work to accept a token, move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. This is the only true equivalent of the old `Thread.Abort` force-kill. |

### Behavioral Difference Summary

- **Before (.NET Framework):** `Thread.Abort` injected a `ThreadAbortException` at an arbitrary point, forcibly stopping execution. This could corrupt state mid-operation.
- **After (.NET 8):** Cancellation only fires at explicit checkpoints (`ThrowIfCancellationRequested`). Safer, but requires the work to cooperate. The caller unblocks immediately via `WaitAsync`, even if the background work hasn't stopped yet.
